════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
ANALYSIS INSTRUCTIONS
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

You must perform a structured, step-by-step analysis. Think carefully before deciding.

Step 0 — CONFLICT PRE-CHECK:
Before reading the rule, scan ALL provided paragraphs and ask:
"Do any two paragraphs address the same legal topic but reach
different conclusions, assign different obligations, or specify
different mechanisms?"

If yes → note the conflicting paragraph IDs now. You MUST address
this conflict in your reason field regardless of the rule being evaluated.

This step exists because conflicts are easy to miss when you are
focused on evaluating compliance. Find them first.

Step 1 — UNDERSTAND THE RULE:
Read the RULE INSTRUCTION carefully. This defines exactly what the contract must contain to
be rated "Good". The RULE DESCRIPTION provides context and the expected standard language.

Step 2 — SCAN EACH PARAGRAPH:
For each paragraph, determine whether it addresses the rule's subject matter. Record the
Paragraph IDs of all relevant paragraphs in para_identifiers. A paragraph is relevant ONLY
if its text explicitly discusses the same legal topic, obligation, or right described in the rule.

Step 3 — CHECK FOR INTER-PARAGRAPH CONFLICTS:
Before evaluating compliance, check whether any two or more paragraphs address the same
legal topic but contain contradictory terms, obligations, or rights. If a conflict exists,
note it explicitly — this affects the risk level regardless of individual paragraph compliance.

Step 4 — EVALUATE COMPLIANCE:
For the relevant paragraphs collectively, determine whether the SPECIFIC TERMS meet the
rule's requirements. Compare numbers, timeframes, scope, conditions, and obligations —
not just whether the topic is mentioned.

Step 5 — ASSIGN RISK LEVEL:
Choose exactly one risk level:

  Good      — The relevant paragraphs collectively satisfy ALL requirements in the INSTRUCTION.
               Specific terms (scope, timeframes, conditions, obligations) MEET OR EXCEED the
               rule's requirements. Good — No deviations. No conflicts between paragraphs.
               If ANY conflict exists between paragraphs on this topic,
               Good is NOT a valid status — minimum Medium applies.

  Low       — The paragraphs largely meet the requirements but have minor deviations or wording
               differences that pose minimal risk. Terms may also be MORE favorable than the
               rule expects.

  Medium    — Notable gap but negotiable. Terms partially meet the rule but fall short in
               specific areas. OR two paragraphs address the same topic with contradictory
               terms. The gap or conflict is notable but negotiable.

  Critical  — Significant deviation or contradiction. Terms materially weaker than required,
               missing key protections the rule demands, or terms that directly contradict the
               rule or contain dangerous provisions. OR a direct conflict between paragraphs
               creates serious legal ambiguity.

  Not Found — NONE of the provided paragraphs contain text relevant to this rule's subject
               matter.

Step 6 — WRITE REASON AND SUGGESTIONS:
  matched_clause_name :
                  Concise human-readable label for the clause this rule reviewed in the
                  contract. Prefer the clause heading copied verbatim from the paragraph
                  text (e.g. "Confidentiality", "Term and Survival", "Governing Law").
                  Max 5 words. Plain text only — no leading numbers, no quotes, no JSON.
                  If status is "Not Found", return an empty string "".

  reason        : 2–4 sentences explaining your verdict. Begin by naming the matched clause
                  (e.g. "The 'Term and Survival' clause states ..."). You MUST cite EXACT
                  text from the paragraphs using direct quotes. If an inter-paragraph
                  conflict exists, you MUST describe it here with quotes from both
                  conflicting paragraphs.

  suggestion    : If risk level is Low, Medium, Critical, or Not Found — describe what should
                  be changed or added. Plain prose. If Good, use empty string.

  suggested_fix : The EXACT replacement clause text that must go into THIS specific
                  contract for THIS specific rule. The user will substitute this string
                  directly into the document without further editing — treat it like a
                  surgical edit, not a template suggestion.

                  STRUCTURAL RULES — the value MUST be:
                    • a single self-contained block of clause text in the same legal
                      register as the contract;
                    • drafted to fit the surrounding contract — same defined terms, same
                      party names that already appear in the matched paragraph;
                    • free of any prefix like "Suggested:", "Consider:", "Replace with:",
                      "Here is the fix:", "You should...", "Recommended clause:";
                    • free of markdown, bullet lists, headings, JSON, code fences,
                      backticks, asterisks, or quotation marks wrapping the whole block;
                    • free of placeholder tokens like "[Party Name]", "[Date]",
                      "[Insert ...]", "<...>" — use the ACTUAL party names, dates and
                      defined terms that appear in the contract paragraphs above. If a
                      value is genuinely unknown, omit it rather than invent a placeholder.

                  SPECIFICITY — NOT BOILERPLATE:
                  Generic boilerplate is a failure. The suggested_fix MUST address the
                  specific deviation you cited in the reason field. Examples:
                    • If the contract says "one (1) year" and the rule requires "three (3)
                      years", the suggested_fix replaces that exact term in the contract's
                      own wording, not a generic survival clause.
                    • If the contract picks the wrong jurisdiction, the suggested_fix is
                      the contract's own governing-law sentence rewritten with the
                      correct jurisdiction — not a generic template clause.
                    • If a required protection is missing, the suggested_fix is the
                      additional sentence(s) that should be inserted, in the contract's
                      voice, citing the contract's own defined terms.
                  A reader should be able to drop your suggested_fix into the contract,
                  remove the original deviating words, and have a clean, working clause.

                  VERBATIM-VALUE RULE — NON-NEGOTIABLE:
                  Every concrete value the rule states (durations, day-counts, percentages,
                  dollar amounts, thresholds, jurisdictions, named parties, statutory
                  references, defined terms) MUST appear in the suggested_fix EXACTLY as
                  written in the RULE INSTRUCTION or RULE DESCRIPTION. Do not round,
                  expand, contract, paraphrase, or substitute these values. If the rule
                  says "30 days", you write "30 days" or "thirty (30) days" — never
                  "60 days", "one month", or any other variant. If the rule says
                  "California", you do not write "Delaware". Inventing a value the rule
                  did not specify is a critical defect — the user may apply your text
                  directly into a binding legal document.

                  SELF-AUDIT BEFORE RETURNING:
                  Re-read the suggested_fix and confirm: (a) it does not start with any
                  meta-prefix; (b) it contains zero markdown or placeholders; (c) every
                  concrete value matches the rule verbatim; (d) it directly fixes the
                  deviation cited in the reason field. If any check fails, rewrite it
                  before returning.

                  If status is Good, return an empty string "".
                  If status is Not Found, return the full new clause text that should be
                  inserted into the contract, in the same register as the surrounding
                  document, with every value copied verbatim from the rule description.

════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
CRITICAL EVALUATION RULES
════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

1. EXISTENCE IS NOT COMPLIANCE:
   A paragraph that MENTIONS the same topic as the rule is NOT automatically "Good". You must
   compare the SPECIFIC TERMS in the paragraph against what the INSTRUCTION requires.
   - Rule expects "three years" but paragraph says "one year" → Medium or Critical
   - Rule expects "mutual obligations" but paragraph is one-sided → Medium or Critical
   - Rule expects "written certification" but paragraph only says "return materials" → Medium or Critical

2. NO CROSS-CONTAMINATION:
   Only use the paragraphs provided above for this rule. Do NOT borrow evidence or text from
   memory of other rules or documents.

3. MISSING PROTECTIONS = NOT "Good":
   If the rule's INSTRUCTION expects a specific protection (e.g., liability cap, notice period,
   cure right, survival clause) and NO paragraph addresses it at all, the risk level is Medium
   or Critical — not Good. Flag the omission explicitly in the reason field.

4. SUBSTANCE OVER FORM:
   Focus on the legal effect and obligations, not just exact wording. Two clauses can use
   different words but have the same legal effect. Judge by substance.

5. DIRECTION MATTERS:
   Terms MORE favorable than the rule expects are rated Good or Low. Note the favorable
   deviation but do not penalize it.

6. AMBIGUITY IS NOT A NEGATIVE VERDICT:
   If text is ambiguous, note the ambiguity in the reason field. Do NOT assume the worst
   interpretation. Assign Medium risk level for genuinely ambiguous provisions.

7. GROUND EVERY CLAIM:
   Every statement in reason must reference specific words or phrases from the paragraph text.
   If you cannot quote specific text to support a claim, do not make that claim.

8. NO HALLUCINATION:
   - Do NOT invent, assume, infer, or fabricate information not explicitly present in the paragraphs.
   - Do NOT rely on external legal knowledge, general contract norms, or industry assumptions.
   - Do NOT paraphrase paragraph text in your quotes — use the EXACT words.
   - If you cannot find relevant text, the status is Not Found. Do not guess.

9. INTER-PARAGRAPH CONFLICTS:
   If two or more provided paragraphs address the same legal topic but contain
   contradictory terms, obligations, or rights — you MUST flag this explicitly
   in the reason field with exact quotes from both conflicting paragraphs.
   Assign at minimum a Medium risk level, regardless of whether each paragraph
   individually appears compliant. A direct conflict that creates serious legal
   ambiguity warrants Critical.

   COMMON CONFLICT PATTERNS — these are ALWAYS Critical:
   - Two paragraphs assign the same dispute to different forums
     (e.g., one says "courts of California", another says "AAA Arbitration")
     → These are mutually exclusive. Do NOT treat them as complementary.
   - Two paragraphs assign the same obligation to different parties
   - Two paragraphs specify different notice periods for the same trigger
   - One paragraph grants a right that another paragraph restricts or removes

   When in doubt: if Party A would argue Paragraph X and Party B would argue
   Paragraph Y to reach opposite outcomes — that is a conflict. Flag it.

DISPUTE FORUM NOTE:
Court jurisdiction and arbitration are mutually exclusive dispute
resolution mechanisms. If one paragraph specifies court jurisdiction
and another specifies arbitration for the same agreement, this is
ALWAYS a Critical conflict — never treat them as complementary or
cumulative. The status must be Critical and the reason must quote
both paragraphs.

